{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_beargrass_ver01/data/sn86075096/00340581702/1949030101/1254.xml":{"full_text":"Market Outlook\nBy GILBERT GUSLER\nFEB, 21. 1949\nBUSINESS ACTIVITY has con\ntinued to ease from the record peak.\nPrice weakness has been spreading\ninto industrial raw materials. Furth\ner layoffs and plant curtailment or\nshutdowns are being reported, al\nthough total industrial production\nis still at an extremely high peace\ntime level. The present downward\ntrend probably will continue.\nWhile a majority of economists do\nnot expect a severe recession, the\nrisk of a snowballing effect when\nbusiness starts down from an ex\ntremely high peak is great.\nConsumer buying power for foods\nand clothing will decline more than\ntotal income because of many rela\ntively fixed living costs. Much of\nthe drop in retail prices from lower\nconsumer incomes will be passed\nback to the producer because of\nrigidity in distribution charges.\nThe farmer's share of the con\nsumer dollar is declining. In Decem\nber 1948, farmers received 51 cents\nof the consumer's food dollar com\npared with 55 cents a year earlier.\nIn 1935-39, they received only 40\ncents.\nAccording to the U. S. depart\nment of agriculture, the annual\ncost of typical foods for a family of\nthree at last December's retail\nprices was $663 compared with \u00a3683\na year previous. The farmer's share\ndecreased to $339 last December\nfrom $373 a year earlier, while\nmarketing charges increased to $324\nfrom $310.\nCATTLE prices during the next\ntwo months probably will be steady\nto weak for the better grades, while\nlow grade slaughter cattle and all\ngrades of stockers and feeders may\nbe steady to slightly higher. Not\nwithstanding heavy sales in the\nlast two months, the number of fed\ncattle still to come to market ap\npears to be relatively large.\nPrices for such cattle have been\nweak during the spring in a ma\njority of past years. The tendency\nmay be aggravated this year by\nfurther decline in consumer demand.\nThe supply of low grade beef cattle\nin the next two or three months\nwill be smallest of the year. Owing\nto shrinking demand, prices for such\ncattle probably will show less\nstrength than usual at this season.\nDemand for stock cattle will\nLivestock Prices on Feb. 22, 1949\nSt. Paul\n$24.00-27.00\n23.50- 27.00\n21.50- 24.50\n21,00-24.00\n18.50- 21.50\n17.00-18.50\n16.50- 24.50\n16.50- 18.50\n14,00-16.50\n18.00-22.50\n11.00-32.00\n13.00-22.00\n16.50- 23.00\n16.50- 22.50\n17.50- 23.50\n14.00-21.00\nBilling\u00ab\nChicago\nCATTLE\nChoice light steers (1,100 lbs. down)\nChoice heavy steers (1,100 lbs. up) 25.00-29.50\n22.50-25.50\n23.00-25.50\n20.00-23.00\n18.50-20.00\nCommon to choice butcher heifers 17.50-26.50\n16.75-19.00\n14.00-16.75\n19,00-23.50\n17.00-32.00\n14.50-29.00\n.$25 00-29.50\n20.50\nGood light steers\nGood heavy steers\nMedium steers (all weights)\nCommon light steers\n18.00-18.50\n\u202215.00-17.00\n15.00-15.50\n11.00-14,00\n\u2022\u202217.00-19.00\n27.00\n19.50-23.50\n14.00-21.00\n18.50\n18.00-23.60\n\u2022\u202212.00-17.00\nMedium and good butcher cows\nCanner, cutter and common cows\nCutter to good bulls\nCull to choice veal calves\nCull to choice calves (500 lbs. down!\nCommon to choice feeders (500-800 lbs.) 18.00-25.00\nCommon to choice feeders (800-1,050 lbs.) 18.00-24.50\nMedium to choice Stocker and feeder calves 19.00-27.00\nMedium to choice stock cows and heifers 15.50-23.50\nHOGS\nHeavy (240 lbs. up), good and choice\nMedium (200-240 lbs.), good and choice\nLight (160-200 lbs.), good and choice 20.50-21.50\nLight lights (120-160 lbs.), good and choice 18,25-21.00\n18.25-20.25\n17.00-18.50\n15.75-17.00\n17.00-19.00\n19.75\n20.75\n19.75-20.75\n17.25-20.50\n20.00-20.50\n20.00-20.75\n17.75-20.50\n20.00-21.25\nLight weights, medium grade\nGood and choice packing sows (270-400 lbs.).\nGood packing sows (400-550 lbs.)\nSlaughter pigs (120 lbs. down)\nStocker and feeder pigs\n16.00-16.00\n18.75\n18.50-19.00\n20.00-20.25\nSHEEP AND LAMBS\nGood and choice lambs\nCommon to good lambs\nCommon to choice ewes\nGood and choice feeder lambs\n\u2022Common and medium.\n\u2022\u2022Medium and good.\n24.25-24.75\n18.50-24.00\n9.50-12.50\n22.00-23.50\n24.25-25.25\n18.50-23.75\n8.50-12.50\n\u2022\u202220.00-22.25\n5.00- 7.00\n15.00-20.50\nbroaden as the spring grazing sen\nson approaches. Supplies probably\nwiM be relatively short because ot\nthe reduced cattle population com\npared with a few years ago, storm\nlosses, and exclusion of Mexican\ncattle. Demand for feeder cattle\nprobably will increase on price dips,\neven though current relationships\nbetween prices for feeders, feed and\nfinished cattle do not appear very\nattractive.\nTotal cattle numbers on farms in\ncreased slightly in 1948, but were\nabout 8 percent lower on Jan. 1\nthan the 1945 peak. Cattle kept\nMarkets at a Glance\nDemand Further shrinkage in consumer\nbuying Dower appears probable.\nCattle\u2014Supply of finished grades probabir\nwill continue heavy in spring months.\nHobs \u2014Early spring price gain is likely to be\nsmall because of shrinking demand and early\nmovement of fall pigs.\nLambs\u2014Decrease of 7 percent in breeding\newes Indicates extremely light 1949 lamb crop.\nWool\u2014Trade observers expect foreign wool\nease year.\nWheat\u2014Price outlook hinges largely on ex\ntent government uses loan stocks for export\nprogram.\nCorn\u2014Price break has cut market receipts\nsharply and accelerated movement into loan.\nFlaxseed\u2014Drop In linseed meal prices has\nslowed crusher demand for flaxseed.\nSeeds\u2014Total supply of hay and forage seeds\nIs 6 percent under last year, 15 percent under\n1943-47 average.\nBy-product Feeds\u2014Prices are not likely to\nrecover major part of decline.\nHay Price advances have been limited\nlargely to storm areas and adjacent sections.\nDairy Products Government will support\ngrade A butter at 59 cents a pound.\nEggs\u2014Price support will continue at sera*\nlevel as In past last.\nPoultry\u2014Commercial broiler and fryer sup\nplies will continue heavy for next three\nmonths.\nPotatoes Price support for 194\u00ab crop wtM\naverage $1.80 per cwt.\nprimarily for beef increased about\n1,000,000 head, or 2.4 percent last\nyear. Storm losses in the west up\nto Feb. 1 were approximately 81,\n000 head. In spite of losses after that\ndate, cattle numbers probably are\nlarger than last year.\nHOG prices probably will have\na further minor rally in the near\nfuture, but it may be over before\nthe end of March. Receipts have\nfallen off materially in the past\nmonth, but, with consumer buying\npower shrinking, price improvement\nhas been small. Since consumer de\nmand may diminish further and the\nfall pig crop, estimated at about 8\npercent over last year, is likely to\nstart to market relatively early, any\nadditional price recovery is not\nlikely to be large or last long,\nOwing to the extremely low price\nfor lard, hogs weighing over 220\npounds probably will continue to\n(Please turn to page 42)\nIf It's POWER You Want\nM a\\e it a\ni\nMASSEY-HARRIS\n3\n'44\" 3-plow power, 24\ncubic inch, 4-cylinder engine, S\nspeeds forward.\nTough spots disappear when you put a Massey-Harris tractor to work on\nyour place. There's more power in Massey-Harris more downright\nlugging ability ot the drawbar more capacity on belt work .more\nreserve, stamina, dependability. It's the result of high compression in\nthe engine, straightline design in the transmission. High compression\ntakes the laziness out of on engine make it peppy, more alive, more\nresponsive. A straight line transmission delivers that power smoothly,\nefficiently you get full power on every belt and field operation.\nThere's a Massey-Harris tractor for your farm 6 great models\n5 power sizes each the power and economy leader in its doss.\nThe Following Items Arc Available /or\nImmediate Delivery\nModel\nMODEL 44 TRACTORS\nWe stiH hove a few Model\n44 tractors in stock. If you are in need of a tractor this spring drop\nin and see the Massey-Harris line.\nGRAIN DRILLS\nSeeding time is drawing near and we have\na limited supply of Model 306 Massey-Harris grain dribs in stock. If\nyou need a drill come in and look them over!\nFLEXIBLE HARROW\nJust received a shipment of flexible\npipe bar harrows. The price is right but the supply is limited.\nTANDEM DISCS\nWe have in stock heavy duty tractor type\ntandem discs equipped with either I 6 or 1 8 inch blades. These discs\nare available in 12 and 15 foot sizes. Don't buy a disc until you\nhave inspected our line of tandem discs.\nCALKINS SEED CLEANERS AND TREATERS\nA cleaner, grader and treater all combined in one well designed com\npact unit. Built in two sizes, the C-101 for the large operator and\nthe C-91 for the smaller operator. Protect your registered seed with\nthis Calkins Cleaner and Treater. Don't take a chance on getting\nyour seed mixed with inferior seed and weed seed.\nWEED SPRAYERS\nhigh or low\nThe Meyers line of weed\nsprayers\npressure pumps in ob sizes and types ore available.\nListen to Our New Radio Show\nMon. Thru Sot.\nWUNDERWALD HAAS\nBULLETIN BOARD\nKMON\niCl\n560\nFree Public Service Program, brought\nto our Parmer Friends on ANY ITEM\nYOU WISH TO ADVERTISE!\nTrade! Lost or Pound! Just send in\nformation to WUNDERWALD HAAS\nBULLETIN BOARD, care of KMON.\nFof\no* your died\n7:15 o. m.\nKMJjJ\nYour M assey-Harris Dealer\nWunderwald Haas\nImplement Co.\nGREAT FALLS\nConrad\nHavre","height":"15993","width":"11136"}}
